The secret is out and you read it here first. Shadows of Luclin will ship with an extra CD that contains a &quot;complete upgrade&quot; to all of the textures in the world of EverQuest. I'll say that again just because it seems important: Shadows of Luclin will ship with an extra CD that contains a &quot;complete upgrade&quot; to all of the textures in the world of EverQuest. <br>
No longer will players have to be content with the 32x32 resolution pixels from the previous games. In the two years since the original game launched, there have been significant improvements in graphics technology that allow for much more sophisticated textures. Art Lead Scott McDaniel and his team &quot;have gone through the entire game and applied the new higher resolution textures by hand.&quot; Shadows of Luclin can now bring 256x256 pixel textures to the game and some of the textures can even go as high as 512x512 pixels. We've got seven pairs of comparisons below that show you just what kind of effect this increase in resolution can have. <br>
<br>
But wait! There's more... <br>
<br>
The team has also included a new alternate advancement system for players over 50th level. Players at that level will have two experience pools -- one for level advancement and one for ability increases. The player can toggle back and forth between either of the pools with no penalty. <br>
<br>
As you accumulate points in your alternate advancement pool, you'll be able to purchase new abilities. Things like &quot;minor permanent statistic and resistance boosts, unique skills based on your class or archetype and general skills&quot; will be available. The various enhancements may even include things like &quot;enhanced metabolism&quot; or &quot;unique skills not yet available to anyone.&quot; Several of the enhancements will open up even more enhancements (and, by extension, justify your continued online existence as a form of self-improvement). Any experience lost when you character dies will be deducted from your leveling pool. <br>
<br>
Shadows of Luclin is quickly becoming as big a deal as the original game was when it was first released. With 24 new zones (we've got screens of some below), huge graphical improvements and horseys, it's more than enough to keep existing players interested<br>
